   "source": [
    "from scipy.stats import pearsonr\n",
    "from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "\n",
    "pearson_r = pearsonr(test_labels, test_predictions)[0]\n",
    "\n",
    "mse = mean_squared_error(\n",
    "    test_labels,\n",
    "    test_predictions\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "rmse = np.sqrt(mse)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Spearman ρ: {test_spearman:.4f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Pearson r : {pearson_r:.4f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"MSE       : {mse:.4f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"RMSE      : {rmse:.4f}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "6f2f5019-f0d9-4f5d-b166-3c0bf0aabe65",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "SBERT was evaluated using cosine similarity between phrase embeddings produced by the all-MiniLM-L6-v2 model on the SemRel2024 Afrikaans test set. \n",
    "With a Spearman correlation coefficient of 0.7162, the model demonstrated a high degree of agreement between the human-annotated gold labels \n",
    "and the projected semantic relatedness scores. The strong positive linear link between anticipated and actual scores is further supported by \n",
    "the Pearson correlation coefficient of 0.7178.\n",
    "\n",
    "With a Mean Squared Error (MSE) of 0.0310 and a Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) of 0.1760, the model's overall prediction errors were \n",
    "comparatively low. These findings imply that SBERT produced a solid baseline for the semantic relatedness test and was successful in \n",
    "capturing semantic links between Afrikaans sentence pairs. The model was able to rank sentence pairs similarly to human annotators \n",
    "while preserving low prediction error, as evidenced by the high correlation values.\n"
   ]
  },
